### Named and Optional Parameters in C#

C# supports named arguments and optional parameters for more flexible method calls.

### Optional Parameters

Parameters with default values that can be omitted when calling:

```csharp
static void Log(string message, string level = "INFO", DateTime? timestamp = null)
{
    var time = timestamp ?? DateTime.Now;
    Console.WriteLine($"[{time}] [{level}] {message}");
}

// Calls
Log("Starting");                    // Uses defaults
Log("Error!", "ERROR");             // Custom level
Log("Debug", "DEBUG", DateTime.Now); // All specified
```

### Rules for Optional Parameters

| Rule | Example |
|------|---------|
| Must come after required parameters | `void Foo(int a, int b = 0)` |
| Default must be compile-time constant | `int x = 5` or `string s = "hi"` |
| Cannot use `this`, `base`, `new` as defaults | - |
| Default is evaluated once at compile time | - |

### Named Arguments

Specify arguments by name instead of position:

```csharp
static void CreateUser(string name, int age, bool isAdmin = false)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"{name}, {age}, Admin: {isAdmin}");
}

// Named arguments
CreateUser(age: 30, name: "Alice");
CreateUser("Bob", isAdmin: true, age: 25);
CreateUser(name: "Charlie", age: 28, isAdmin: false);
```

### Combining Named and Positional

```csharp
// Positional first, then named
CreateUser("Dave", isAdmin: true, age: 35);

// Named out of order (C# 7.2+)
CreateUser(age: 40, name: "Eve");
```

### Benefits of Named Arguments

| Benefit | Example |
|---------|---------|
| Readability | `Parse(input: text, format: "json")` |
| Skip optional params | `Method(required1: a, optional3: c)` |
| Reorder arguments | `Method(z: 3, x: 1, y: 2)` |
| Documentation | Clear intent at call site |

### Overload Resolution

Named arguments help resolve ambiguous overloads:

```csharp
static void Display(int x, int y) { }
static void Display(string x, string y) { }

Display(x: 5, y: 10);  // Calls the int version
```

> **Key Point:** Optional parameters must appear after all required parameters. Named arguments can appear in any order, but positional arguments must come before named ones. Use named arguments to improve readability when a method has many parameters or multiple parameters of the same type.

### params with Optional

```csharp
static void Log(string message, params object[] args)
{
    // params must be last, cannot have default
}
```

codeExample:
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        // Optional parameters
        PrintOrder("Laptop", 1);           // Uses default: urgent=false
        PrintOrder("Mouse", 2, true);      // Urgent

        // Named arguments
        PrintOrder(quantity: 5, product: "Keyboard");
        PrintOrder(product: "Monitor", urgent: true);
    }

    static void PrintOrder(string product, int quantity = 1, bool urgent = false)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{product} x{quantity} {(urgent ? "(URGENT)" : "")}");
    }
}
